<div id="review_3821446660" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3821446660" />
    <a title="Bryan Alkire" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/72479728-bryan-alkire"><img alt="Bryan Alkire" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1613140523p2/72479728.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3821446660?book_show_action=true">Feb 06, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Bryan Alkire" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Bryan Alkire" href="/user/show/72479728-bryan-alkire">Bryan Alkire</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3821446660" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10036784521150133049">This one is not very good and I was disappointed with it. I liked the concept of a contrary history of early Christianity but this one turned quickly into a polemic. It failed to have any balance or perspective. The implication of this book is that all early Christians were religious zealots who formed mobs to destroy religious polytheism in the name of purity. I’m not religious but I figure human nature is human nature and I figure the vast majority of early Christians weren’t firebrands bent o</span>
  <span id="freeText10036784521150133049" style="display:none">This one is not very good and I was disappointed with it. I liked the concept of a contrary history of early Christianity but this one turned quickly into a polemic. It failed to have any balance or perspective. The implication of this book is that all early Christians were religious zealots who formed mobs to destroy religious polytheism in the name of purity. I’m not religious but I figure human nature is human nature and I figure the vast majority of early Christians weren’t firebrands bent on destruction. Now, many of their leaders were, but that would be overgeneralizing to a population. The book is at it’s best early. The discussion of monks blaming their straying thoughts on demons is amusing and the chapter on how the Roman authorities actually dealt with Christians is instructive. But, once the book gets to the actual destruction, it becomes a litany of mobs destroying statues, objects and whole temples. I hate the destruction of property generally so I felt emotional at the thought of all these beautiful objects and places destroyed or mutilated just because some group’s leader decreed it not of their religion or just liking it. It helped me out that the writing is fairly dry, so I could keep a fair bit of detachment. In fact, the only part which isn’t dry are the accounts of the destruction. So, all in all, good idea, disappointing and flawed execution. <br /> </span>
  <a data-text-id="10036784521150133049" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


