        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4000503686" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14301949171322596205">This book gives us the story of the destructive spread of early christianity in the Greco-Roman world. The polytheistic world with its all-inclusive nature did not define itself as being opposed to any other religion or sect. But here we see under the expansionist monotheism which can only define itself in an &quot;Us vs Them&quot; way, a near total destruction of the pluralistic and intellectually vibrant pagan world.<br/><br/>The deliberate destruction of art and architecture, the burnings of libraries and the pe</span>
  <span id="freeText14301949171322596205" style="display:none">This book gives us the story of the destructive spread of early christianity in the Greco-Roman world. The polytheistic world with its all-inclusive nature did not define itself as being opposed to any other religion or sect. But here we see under the expansionist monotheism which can only define itself in an "Us vs Them" way, a near total destruction of the pluralistic and intellectually vibrant pagan world.<br /><br />The deliberate destruction of art and architecture, the burnings of libraries and the persecution the polytheists described here is very similar to what happened in India during the invasions of the barbaric Islamic hordes. This short book in fact shows us the violence , barbarity and the anti-intellectualism that is inherent in an expansionist monotheism or any mono-cultures.</span>
